The paper deals with the problem of collective argument evaluation, which involves aggregating the opinions of multiple agents on how a given set of arguments should be evaluated. This problem is relevant to several areas of computer science, including artificial intelligence (cs.AI), game theory (cs.GT), machine learning (cs.LG), multi-agent systems (cs.MA), and social choice (cs.SI). The paper's focus on Pareto optimality and strategy proofness suggests that it is more likely to belong to cs.GT and cs.SI, but the use of argumentation theory and aggregation operators also makes cs.AI, cs.LG, and cs.MA plausible categories.
